WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.480
So hi, my name is Harvey Lieberman and I'm here today to tell you a little bit about

00:00:10.480 --> 00:00:16.959
the R in Pharma organisation, who we are, what we do and how you can get involved if

00:00:16.959 --> 00:00:25.719
you're interested. So R is ubiquitous within the pharmaceutical industry, but until recently

00:00:25.719 --> 00:00:31.160
there hasn't really been a group that works across multiple pharma companies to provide

00:00:31.160 --> 00:00:39.459
a space for users to interact. So in 2017, a group of R users from several pharma companies

00:00:39.459 --> 00:00:45.639
got together with other organisations interested in this space, such as the FDA and Harvard

00:00:45.639 --> 00:00:55.000
to form a group and that's how R Pharma was born. R Pharma is an R consortium, ISC working

00:00:55.000 --> 00:01:01.040
group. It's organised by a group of volunteers from multiple organisations and some of the

00:01:01.040 --> 00:01:10.639
companies involved in setting up the R in Pharma conference are listed on this slide.

00:01:10.639 --> 00:01:19.440
Now the goal of R Pharma has been to host a scientifically and industry oriented conference

00:01:19.440 --> 00:01:24.879
focused on the use of R in the development of pharmaceuticals. Conference covers topics

00:01:24.879 --> 00:01:33.080
such as genomics, drug discovery, PKPD, clinical trials, regulatory compliance and validation,

00:01:33.080 --> 00:01:40.339
as well as more general topics such as reproducible research and DevOps. The focus is on the use

00:01:40.339 --> 00:01:47.680
of R as a primary but not necessarily exclusive tool in the drug development process. We also

00:01:47.680 --> 00:01:54.680
hold workshops at the conference, but since the primary focus is for R practitioners,

00:01:54.680 --> 00:02:00.300
the workshops are really aimed at those who are already competent in R. Anyone's welcome

00:02:00.300 --> 00:02:04.680
to present a workshop and we're lucky to have some really amazing presenters as you'll see

00:02:04.680 --> 00:02:14.199
on some of the later slides. Now, there are plenty of data science conferences, workshops

00:02:14.199 --> 00:02:22.000
and even organisations. So what makes us different? Well, for one, we're run by Pharma

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:28.080
for Pharma. We concentrate on R, which is not to say we don't have contributing talks

00:02:28.080 --> 00:02:36.440
that include Python, SAS or even Julia, but just that R is the main focus. The R in Pharma

00:02:36.440 --> 00:02:43.880
conference that we've held the past three years has been free. Any cost has been assumed

00:02:43.880 --> 00:02:49.039
by an advisory group, which is generally made up of Pharma companies willing to support

00:02:49.039 --> 00:02:54.639
the cross fertilisation that occurs when you put a bunch of curious programmers together.

00:02:54.639 --> 00:03:02.600
In a similar vein, we have no sponsors and nor do we allow sponsorship at the conference

00:03:02.600 --> 00:03:09.039
or any events because we believe that community led effort works best when there's no outside

00:03:09.039 --> 00:03:16.320
influence. We're also focused on diversity and have goals on providing travel grants

00:03:16.320 --> 00:03:23.000
to those who need assistance in attending the meetings. So why am I here today? Well,

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:29.000
I hope you'll understand that the RFOMA is a very open organisation made up of volunteers.

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:33.479
We'd welcome anyone wishing to get involved from presenting at a meeting to reaching out

00:03:33.479 --> 00:03:38.220
to the community with a question and more on how you can get involved in 2021 a little

00:03:38.399 --> 00:03:44.380
later. But first, I'd like to share some information on how we've evolved since 2018.

00:03:44.380 --> 00:03:53.660
RFOMA holds a conference each year. The first was held in 2018 at Harvard. And if you're

00:03:53.660 --> 00:03:59.220
unable to attend, many of the presentations are available on the RFOMA website. The links

00:03:59.220 --> 00:04:06.179
on this slide and I invite you to peruse them. We had around 150 attendees, which was limited

00:04:06.179 --> 00:04:12.020
by the size of the venue, and it ran over two days. We're lucky to have some really

00:04:12.020 --> 00:04:18.059
amazing keynotes that are listed here. There are a number of amazing general presentations

00:04:18.059 --> 00:04:26.339
that range from RNA sequencing to how to convert statisticians to data scientists to using

00:04:26.339 --> 00:04:35.940
our energy XP environment. One thing that was clear from 2018 was that Shiny was the

00:04:35.940 --> 00:04:46.100
main focus of most presenters work. In 2019, we repeated the conference, this time expanding

00:04:46.100 --> 00:04:51.019
to longer workshops each half a day. Once again, the conference was held at Harvard,

00:04:51.019 --> 00:04:56.739
with a mixture of keynotes and general presentations for around 150 attendees. I'd really like

00:04:56.739 --> 00:05:02.100
to highlight the workshops here. We reached out to a number of workshop presenters, all

00:05:02.100 --> 00:05:08.220
of whom agreed to put together a half day workshop at no cost. And all the workshop

00:05:08.220 --> 00:05:14.019
materials and many of the presentations are available through the RFOMA website. What

00:05:14.019 --> 00:05:20.239
was interesting in 2019, there was still a focus on Shiny, but there was a huge focus

00:05:20.239 --> 00:05:30.359
on reproducibility. So, like many other groups in 2020, early on, we decided to switch to

00:05:30.359 --> 00:05:37.640
a fully virtual conference. This provided few benefits over historical in-person meeting.

00:05:37.640 --> 00:05:46.279
First, we could reach more attendees and we received over 500 registrations from 26 countries.

00:05:46.279 --> 00:05:52.559
We were expecting around 300 and initially had prepared for up to 500. But as soon as

00:05:52.559 --> 00:05:59.799
it opened, it was clear that we were going to hit 1,000 plus. And the graph on the right

00:05:59.799 --> 00:06:05.559
is actually really interesting. It shows the registration. This was registration without

00:06:05.559 --> 00:06:12.679
advertising. So, just through word of mouth, it's amazing how quickly we had registration.

00:06:12.679 --> 00:06:18.279
Secondly, we could attract more presenters because people didn't have to travel. There

00:06:18.279 --> 00:06:24.760
were more people willing to present. In fact, we had over 200 proposals for presentations.

00:06:24.760 --> 00:06:30.440
Conference was held over three days, each four hours long, running in the morning for

00:06:30.440 --> 00:06:37.200
those on the West Coast of the US and the evenings in Europe. So, I also want to highlight

00:06:37.200 --> 00:06:42.679
the workshops that were held for the 2020 conference. Because of the virtual nature,

00:06:42.679 --> 00:06:47.600
we could organize a little bit differently and stretched out over multiple days. We ran

00:06:47.600 --> 00:06:53.200
a total of 11 workshops through the week before the conference, each three to four hours long.

00:06:53.200 --> 00:06:57.959
There's some incredible presenters who put a lot of time and effort into building them.

00:06:57.959 --> 00:07:04.239
And all the environments were pre-configured under RStudio Cloud. So, it was very easy

00:07:04.279 --> 00:07:10.119
for people to come in, use the materials and access them afterwards. Once again, these

00:07:10.119 --> 00:07:17.000
were all put on by the presenters at no charge. And once again, the conference is free anyway.

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:25.720
So, it was a really amazing piece of work. Our pharma meeting for 2021 is almost certainly

00:07:25.720 --> 00:07:31.000
going to be a fully virtual event. And thinking about the trends we've seen over the past

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:36.799
three years, R is definitely growing within the pharma and biotech industries at quite

00:07:36.799 --> 00:07:42.760
a rate. We now have more mature infrastructures in place, and there's definitely a move towards

00:07:42.760 --> 00:07:48.720
more submissions using R. In addition, there's greater work in combining languages, such

00:07:48.720 --> 00:07:57.799
as R and Python and R and SAS. I want to switch gears just a little bit and talk about something

00:07:57.799 --> 00:08:06.239
new. We'll be launching a learning and development platform this year called LearnRinPharma.com.

00:08:06.239 --> 00:08:11.399
And the goal of this is to help pharma professionals develop the skills needed in the drug development

00:08:11.399 --> 00:08:17.679
space. The RINPharma group will be helping community members put on workshops, lectures,

00:08:17.679 --> 00:08:23.040
teaching labs in cloud environments with the aim of building practical R skills in a friendly

00:08:23.040 --> 00:08:30.040
environment. At a very high level, what we're hoping to do is to put together a monthly

00:08:30.040 --> 00:08:36.400
write-up on a topic and then follow it by a lecture or workshop, even a workflow, maybe

00:08:36.400 --> 00:08:41.640
a community discussion. This is one way that you, the pharma community, can contribute.

00:08:41.640 --> 00:08:46.520
If you'd like to lead a discussion group, teach a lab, please get in touch with us.

00:08:46.520 --> 00:08:52.200
Contact details will be on the final slide. And keep an eye out for LearnRinPharma.com.

00:08:52.200 --> 00:08:56.880
We'll announce more through a Twitter feed and the RINPharma website.

00:09:01.320 --> 00:09:07.280
The first RINPharma conference that we held three years ago was dominated by Shiny apps.

00:09:07.280 --> 00:09:14.280
We can see how Shiny can play a role in modernizing the drug submission process, but it's fraught

00:09:14.280 --> 00:09:21.520
with challenges. These can be related to technology, regulatory agencies, training

00:09:21.520 --> 00:09:32.159
and validation, qualification, and even people and culture, plus others. In 2021, our pharma

00:09:32.159 --> 00:09:37.520
wants to tackle Shiny for submissions as part of LearnRinPharma.com.

00:09:37.520 --> 00:09:47.200
RINPharma is all about the community helping the community. This year, we're looking to

00:09:47.200 --> 00:09:53.719
launch LearnRinPharma.com, which I spoke about. So if you have an idea for a write-up followed

00:09:53.719 --> 00:10:00.359
by a lecture, workshop, discussion, please reach out through the website, email or Twitter.

00:10:00.359 --> 00:10:06.799
We can help you find like-minded people, provide logistics. Some examples might be combining

00:10:06.880 --> 00:10:14.400
R and Python or building a validation framework. Shiny for submissions will be part of this too.

00:10:15.599 --> 00:10:20.799
Finally, a huge thank you to all of the presenters and workshop hosts over the past three years,

00:10:20.799 --> 00:10:24.239
putting so much effort, along with the advisory groups and Harvard,

00:10:24.239 --> 00:10:28.880
who have supported the conferences that we've held. And I thank you for your attention.

00:10:36.799 --> 00:10:37.299
Thank you.

